ions Project gathers an accomplished interdisciplinary team of scholars—members of the Reparations Planning Committee—who have considered the issues pertinent to making reparations happen. This book will be an essential resource in the national conversation going forward. The first section of The Black Reparations Project crystallizes the rationale for reparations, cataloguing centuries of racial repression, discrimination, violence, mass incarceration, and the immense black-white wealth gap. Drawing on the contributors’ expertise in economics, history, law, public policy, public health, and education, the second section unfurls direct guidance for building and implementing a reparations program, including draft legislation that addresses how the program should be financed and how claimants can be identified and compensated. Rigorous and comprehensive, The Black Reparations Project will motivate, guide, and speed the final leg of the journey for justice.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2024) 0aAfrican AmericansxReparations. 0aAfrican AmericansxSocial conditions. 0aRacial justicezUnited StatesvHandbooks, manuals, etc. 0aRacismzUnited States. 0aReparations for historical injusticeszUnited States. 0aSlaveryzUnited States. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / Economics / General.2bisacsh1 aBellamy, Wesley, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBentley-Edwards, Keisha L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrown, Lisa R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCraemer, Thomas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDarity, William A, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDarity, William A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDarity, William, 